---
export const prerender = true;
import BlogLayout from '../../layouts/BlogLayout.astro';
import '../../styles/global.css';
---

<BlogLayout
  title="Is CH a Scrabble Word? SOWPODS Only — NOT Valid in TWL (7 Points)"
  description="CH is valid in SOWPODS (Collins) but NOT in TWL. Worth 7 points (C=3, H=4), CH is a Scottish/Welsh dialectal word for 'I'. A rare consonant-only high-scoring play."
  keywords="is ch a scrabble word, ch scrabble valid, ch sowpods only, ch scottish i, ch 7 points scrabble, consonant only scrabble words"
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "Is CH a Scrabble Word? SOWPODS Only — NOT Valid in TWL (7 Points)",
    "description": "CH is valid in SOWPODS (Collins) but NOT in TWL. Worth 7 points, CH is a Scottish/Welsh dialectal word for 'I'.",
    "datePublished": "2026-06-29",
    "author": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "ScrabbleWordsFinder.com", "url": "https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com" },
    "publisher": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "ScrabbleWordsFinder.com" },
    "mainEntityOfPage": { "@type": "WebPage", "@id": "https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com/blog/is-ch-a-scrabble-word" }
  })} />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "Is CH a valid Scrabble word?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "CH is valid ONLY in SOWPODS (Collins Scrabble Words). It is NOT valid in TWL (Tournament Word List) used in North American play. It scores 7 points (C=3, H=4)." } },
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "What does CH mean?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "CH is a Scottish and Welsh dialectal word meaning 'I' (the first person pronoun). It's an archaic/dialectal form still found in some Celtic-influenced English dialects. Collins includes it as a legitimate English word." } },
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "Is CH the only consonant-only two-letter word in Scrabble?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "In SOWPODS, CH joins SH, MM, and HM as consonant-only two-letter words. SH and HM are valid in both dictionaries, while CH and MM are SOWPODS-only. These are valuable for consonant-heavy racks." } }
    ]
  })} />

  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-12">
    <article class="prose prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose flex items-center gap-1">
        <a href="/blog/" class="hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">← Blog</a>
        <span class="mx-1">›</span>
        <span class="text-gray-300">Two-Letter Words</span>
      </nav>
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Is CH a Scrabble Word? SOWPODS Only — NOT Valid in TWL</h1>
      <div class="not-prose mb-8 flex items-center gap-3 text-sm text-gray-400">
        <time datetime="2026-06-29">June 29, 2026</time>
        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-600"></span>
        <span>4 min read</span>
        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-600"></span>
        <a href="/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">🔤</span> Word Finder</a>
      </div>
      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-300 mb-8">CH — a Scottish/Welsh dialectal pronoun meaning "I" — is one of the most unusual two-letter words in SOWPODS. At 7 points and using only consonants, CH is a powerful tool for clearing consonant-heavy racks in international play. But be careful: it's completely invalid in TWL and will lose your turn in North American tournaments.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-8 p-6 rounded-2xl border-2 border-orange-500/50 bg-gradient-to-r from-orange-950/30 to-amber-950/20 relative overflow-hidden">
        <div class="absolute top-3 right-4 text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-orange-500/70">⚠ SOWPODS Only</div>
        <p class="text-2xl font-black text-white tracking-wider mb-2">CH</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-orange-300 font-semibold mb-3">7 points · C(3) + H(4) · Scottish/Welsh: "I" · SOWPODS only · Consonant-only</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">CH is valid in Collins (international) but INVALID in TWL (North America). A rare consonant-only play scoring 7 points without using any vowels from your rack.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-orange-500/30 bg-orange-950/10">
        <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-6 text-center">
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-orange-400">7</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Points</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-red-400">✗</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Invalid TWL</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-green-400">✓</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Valid SOWPODS</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-orange-400">0</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Vowels Used</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">What Does CH Mean?</h2>
      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">📖 Definition</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">CH is a <span class="text-white font-medium">Scottish and Welsh dialectal form of "I" (first person singular pronoun)</span>. It appears in Celtic-influenced English dialects where it survived from older forms. Collins includes it as a legitimate English word reflecting dialectal usage across Scotland and Wales.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Consonant-Only Two-Letter Words</h2>
      <p>CH belongs to a rare category — two-letter words with no vowels at all:</p>
      <div class="not-prose my-6 flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-3">
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-green-700 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">SH</span><span class="text-green-400 text-xs">5pts Both</span></span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-green-700 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">HM</span><span class="text-green-400 text-xs">7pts Both</span></span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-orange-700 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">CH</span><span class="text-orange-400 text-xs">7pts SOWPODS</span></span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-orange-700 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">MM</span><span class="text-orange-400 text-xs">6pts SOWPODS</span></span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-green-700 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">MY</span><span class="text-green-400 text-xs">7pts Both*</span></span>
      </div>
      <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 text-center mt-2">*MY/BY use Y as vowel sound but technically no A/E/I/O/U tiles</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Dictionary Status</h2>
      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-500/30 bg-red-950/10"><p class="text-red-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✗ INVALID in TWL (NASPA)</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Not in Tournament Word List. CH is considered too dialectal for North American competitive play. Playing it in TWL games loses your turn.</p></div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10"><p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✓ Valid in SOWPODS (Collins)</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Accepted in Collins Scrabble Words. Collins includes many Celtic-influenced dialect words. Legal in international tournaments and UK/Australian clubs.</p></div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">When to Play CH</h2>
      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors"><p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Consonant overload:</span> Stuck with BCDFGH and one vowel? CH dumps two consonants for 7 points while preserving your only vowel for a longer play next turn.</p></div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors"><p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">H premium targeting:</span> H on a double-letter = 11pts total. H on triple-letter = 15pts! CH is an excellent vehicle for delivering H to premium squares.</p></div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors"><p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Cross-word utility:</span> C and H each form many valid two-letter pairs. H works with virtually every vowel (AH, EH, OH, UH) making parallel plays with CH highly productive.</p></div>
      </div>

      <aside class="border-t border-gray-800 mt-12 pt-8 not-prose">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Related Articles</h3>
        <div class="grid gap-3">
          <a href="/blog/is-sh-a-scrabble-word/" class="flex items-center gap-3 p-3 rounded-lg border border-gray-800 hover:border-blue-700 hover:bg-blue-900/10 transition-all group"><span class="text-blue-500 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform">→</span><span class="text-sm text-gray-300 group-hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">Is SH a Scrabble Word? Consonant-Only Play</span></a>
          <a href="/blog/is-mm-a-scrabble-word/" class="flex items-center gap-3 p-3 rounded-lg border border-gray-800 hover:border-blue-700 hover:bg-blue-900/10 transition-all group"><span class="text-blue-500 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform">→</span><span class="text-sm text-gray-300 group-hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">Is MM a Scrabble Word? Double-Consonant Play</span></a>
        </div>
      </aside>

      <div class="not-prose mt-10 p-5 bg-gradient-to-r from-blue-50 to-cyan-50 dark:from-blue-900/20 dark:to-cyan-900/20 border border-blue-200 dark:border-blue-800 rounded-xl shadow-sm">
        <div class="flex items-center justify-between gap-4 flex-wrap">
          <p class="text-sm text-blue-800 dark:text-blue-300 font-medium">🔤 Check any word's validity instantly — free, realtime, no sign-up</p>
          <a href="/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 rounded-lg bg-blue-600 hover:bg-blue-700 text-white text-sm font-semibold transition-colors shadow-sm">Open Word Finder →</a>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="not-prose mt-8 text-center">
        <a href="/blog/" class="text-sm text-gray-400 hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">← Back to all articles</a>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</BlogLayout>
